snippet.title: How to make a face mask quick
snippet.description:
****Disclosure: This video does not include any medical advice or tip about the recent COVID-19 virus. It only has the pattern and tutorial for how to make face masks in bulk for donations.*****

If you want to learn more about sewing or find sewing patterns go to our site: https://www.mygoldenthimble.com/ 

There is no more denying it. The virus is here and we are needed.

I am making this video because I was asked by my hubby's hospital to make face masks to donate as they have none at the moment and they really need them.

As they need A LOT OF FACE MASKS and probably others will need more I am showing you the way I am doing it to save time and make more in a more effective way.

We as seamstresses have joined in the past to help our community and today shouldn't be any different.

The reason I am not indicating any specific material (other than saying that I used non-woven and that is why I am not finishing seams here) it is because I am no authority or have any expertise on the subject and I don't want to promote misinformation.

If you want to donate your skills and make facemasks for your local hospitals reach out to them and ask them what is the best material to make them from. They know better.

Please share this video so we can find more seamstresses whiling to donate their time and skills to our doctors, nurses and sick people who need them.

Thank you so much. Please stay safe, stay at home.
My Golden Thimble

snippet.title: Nuns make face masks to help halt pandemic spread
snippet.description:
(19 Apr 2020) LEAD IN : 
Nuns in a remote Russian convent are making face masks to tackle the shortage of protective wear during the COVID-19 outbreak.

STORY-LINE:
This is a tightly run production line. 
Everyone knows their job and works as a team to produce around 100 face masks each day. 
The workers are nuns who live at a remote Russian Orthodox monastery in Russia's Yaroslav region.
They're doing their bit in the effort to stop the spread of the COVID-19 virus. 
Abbess Erotiyida, Head of St. Nicholas-Solbinsky monastery explains that the monastery is at the heart of the local community. 
 "The idea is very simple - we need to help people. Because if people need them (face masks) and pharmacies cannot provide those means of self-protection, we are always here. The monastery always responds to peoples' needs.  Our monastery is focused on people,  we educate children, we have a college and a school here. Because we are in the remote place people gravitate towards our monastery, all villages come to use with any problems, that's why we are promptly reacting to all needs. The church is always next to people, that's what the history tells us. Our monastery too, during WWII was helping to make clothes for the army," she says.
The sisters are helped by local volunteers and students of the school based in the convent grounds. 
Sister Tamara says that each of them is an expert in their role: "We sew masks in the sewing workshop of the monastery. We are dividing the job. Mainly sisters are taking part in the process, but also pupils from the college are joining us. All perform the duty they are familiar with. Those who knows how to stitch, they are stitching, others are making patterns, some are pinning down and ironing. We are trying to involve as many people as possible who can help us. And when they have possibility everyone comes to help."
Masks are made with four-layers of fabric that is breathable, the outside layer has a brighter colour to cheer the spirits in these difficult times. 
To make the masks, the monastery has bought 4 km of fabric and are donating the finished masks for free to hospitals and other organisations where they are needed. 
The work room is carefully disinfected several times a day explains Sister Suyzanna: "Because we are making masks for the face that are needed to protect from viruses it is necessary to make them in good sanitary conditions. Therefore, before our shift, we are disinfecting our workplaces. We are disinfecting places every hour or an hour and a half. So to keep it clean during the day."
Currently, there are 40 sisters living in the monastery. It has a children's home, a college, a kindergarten and a nursery on site. 
The Russian Orthodox church celebrates Easter this year on April 19 2020. 
 Abbess Erotiyida says that a job done with a prayer brings love and recovery. 
"In the monastery, every job is done with prayer. That's why it is blessed with prayer and love for the people. And I think it is the first step to recovery."
For most people, the new coronavirus causes mild or moderate symptoms, such as fever and cough that clear up in two to three weeks. For some, especially older adults and people with existing health problems, it can cause more severe illness, including pneumonia and death. The vast majority of people recover.

Everyone knows their job and works as a team to produce around 100 face masks each day. 
The workers are nuns who live at a remote Russian Orthodox monastery in Russia's Yaroslav region.
They're doing their bit in the effort to stop the spread of the COVID-19 virus. 
Abbess Erotiyida, Head of St. Nicholas-Solbinsky monastery explains that the monastery is at the heart of the local community. 
 "The idea is very simple - we need to help people. Because if people need them (face masks) and pharmacies cannot provide those means of self-protection, we are always here. The monastery always responds to peoples' needs.  Our monastery is focused on people,  we educate children, we have a college and a school here. Because we are in the remote place people gravitate towards our monastery, all villages come to use with any problems, that's why we are promptly reacting to all needs. The church is always next to people, that's what the history tells us. Our monastery too, during WWII was helping to make clothes for the army," she says.
The sisters are helped by local volunteers and students of the school based in the convent grounds. 
Sister Tamara says that each of them is an expert in their role: "We sew masks in the sewing workshop of the monastery. We are dividing the job. Mainly sisters are taking part in the process, but also pupils from the college are joining us. All perform the duty they are familiar with. Those who knows how to stitch, they are stitching, others are making patterns, some are pinning down and ironing. We are trying to involve as many people as possible who can help us. And when they have possibility everyone comes to help."
Masks are made with four-layers of fabric that is breathable, the outside layer has a brighter colour to cheer the spirits in these difficult times. 
To make the masks, the monastery has bought 4 km of fabric and are donating the finished masks for free to hospitals and other organisations where they are needed. 
The work room is carefully disinfected several times a day explains Sister Suyzanna: "Because we are making masks for the face that are needed to protect from viruses it is necessary to make them in good sanitary conditions. Therefore, before our shift, we are disinfecting our workplaces. We are disinfecting places every hour or an hour and a half. So to keep it clean during the day."
Currently, there are 40 sisters living in the monastery. It has a children's home, a college, a kindergarten and a nursery on site. 
The Russian Orthodox church celebrates Easter this year on April 19 2020. 
 Abbess Erotiyida says that a job done with a prayer brings love and recovery. 
"In the monastery, every job is done with prayer. That's why it is blessed with prayer and love for the people. And I think it is the first step to recovery."
For most people, the new coronavirus causes mild or moderate symptoms, such as fever and cough that clear up in two to three weeks. For some, especially older adults and people with existing health problems, it can cause more severe illness, including pneumonia and death. The vast majority of people recover.
